'''Anne Nolan''' (born 12 November 1950) is an Irish singer, songwriter and author. She was a member of [[the Nolans]].<ref name="EPM">{{cite book |first=Colin|last=Larkin|title= The Encyclopedia of Popular Music 3rd Edition Volume V: Louvin, Charlie-Paul, Clarence |year=1998|publisher=Macmillan|location=London|isbn=0-333-74134-X|page=3969}}</ref>

== Early life ==
Anne Nolan was born in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], to Tommy (26 September 1925–1998) and Maureen Nolan (15 December 1926 – 30 December 2007). She is the second of eight siblings and the oldest of the Nolan sisters, preceding [[Denise Nolan|Denise]], [[Maureen Nolan|Maureen]], [[Linda Nolan|Linda]], [[Bernie Nolan|Bernie]], and [[Coleen Nolan|Coleen]], respectively; she also has two brothers, Tommy and Brian.<ref name="EPM" /> The family lived in [[Raheny]], a suburb of [[Dublin]], before moving to [[Blackpool]], [[England]], in 1962.<ref name="EPM" />

== The Nolans ==
{{Main articles|The Nolans}}
Anne, along with her sisters, was a part of the singing group [[the Nolans]]. The Nolans had a number one hit in 1979 with their song [[I'm in the Mood for Dancing]]. It charted at number two on the Irish music chart, and was number one on charts in Japan and South Africa. Anne left the group for a short period of time, between 1980 and 1982, with her sister Coleen stepping in for Anne. During Anne's two-year absence from the group, they won the 1981 [[Tokyo Music Festival]] with their song "Sexy Music".

Anne reunited with the Nolans as a five-piece (including Bernie, Coleen, Linda and Maureen) for a one-off performance of "I'm In the Mood for Dancing" for BBC One's ''All Time Greatest Party Songs'', hosted by [[Tess Daly]], which aired on 17 December 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0496222/|title=All-Time Greatest Party Songs (2005)|website=IMDb.com|date=17 December 2005|access-date=4 July 2013}}</ref> They performed the song again on 9 August 2007 on ''Loose Women'',<ref name="lw mdb">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1083709/ |title="Loose Women" Episode #11.149 (2007)|access-date= 22 April 2008 |website=IMDb.com |date=9 August 2007}}</ref> but dismissed any immediate prospect of a full-scale reunion.<ref name="reunion">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z2SFXfcCams  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211212/Z2SFXfcCams| archive-date=2021-12-12 |url-status=live|title=Loose Women- The Nolans interview|access-date=5 April 2008 |work= Youtube.com}}{{cbignore}} Uploaded copy of interview.</ref> Anne has only missed out on one reunion, which took place in 2009. She returned yet again in 2020, when they reformed, and remained in the group until its disbandment in 2022.

== Later works ==
Anne released her autobiography, titled ''Anne's Song'', on 27 March 2008.<ref name="Annesong">{{cite web |url=http://www.randomhouse.co.uk/catalog/book.htm?command=search&db=main.txt&eqisbndata=1846053471 |title=Random House:Book Details for Anne's Song |access-date=31 March 2008 |publisher=Random House}}</ref> In the book, co-written with Richard Barber, Anne said she had been repeatedly sexually abused by her father,<ref name="AnneMirror">{{cite news |first=Sarah |last=Wallis |title=Nolans singer Anne was sexually abused by father Tommy |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/showbiz/latest/2008/03/10/nolans-singer-anne-was-sexually-abused-by-father-tommy-89520-20346447/ |work=Daily Mirror |date=10 March 2008 |access-date=31 March 2008}}{{dead link |date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref name="Ireland">{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/news-gossip/im-in-the-mood-for-telling-1339732.html |title=I'm in the mood for telling |last=Dwyer |first=Ciara |date=7 April 2008 |work=Irish Independent |access-date=7 April 2008}}</ref> from the age of 11 until she was 15 or 16.<ref>[http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/daily-feature/The-dark-secret-of-Anne.3864205.jp The dark secret of Anne Nolan], blackpoolgazette.co.uk; accessed 22 February 2016.</ref>

